  "question": {
    "context": "A spherical water tank needs to be painted on the outer surface. It has a diameter of 8 meters.",
    "given_information": "Diameter = 8 meters",
    "question": "A special paint is used that can cover 10 square meters per liter.  How many liters of paint will be needed to cover the entire surface of the tank? Assume you cannot buy fractions of liters.",
    "difficulty_level": "medium 6/10"
  },
  "difficulty": "medium",
  "reasoning": "This question tests the student's ability to: \n\n1. **Understand and apply the formula for the surface area of a sphere.**\n2. **Perform unit conversions (diameter to radius).**\n3. **Use the calculated surface area to solve a real-world problem involving paint coverage.**\n\n**Solution:**\n\n1. **Calculate the radius:**\n   - Radius (r) = Diameter / 2 = 8 meters / 2 = 4 meters\n\n2. **Calculate the surface area of the sphere:**\n   - Surface Area (SA) = 4πr² = 4 * π * (4 meters)² = 64π square meters\n\n3. **Calculate the liters of paint needed:**\n   - Liters of paint = Surface Area / Coverage per liter \n   - Liters of paint = 64π square meters / 10 square meters/liter ≈ 20.11 liters\n\n4. **Round up to the nearest whole liter:**\n   - Since we cannot buy fractions of liters, we need to round 20.11 liters up to 21 liters.\n\n**Therefore, 21 liters of paint are needed to cover the entire surface of the tank.**"
},
